  "prompt": "Are there international laws against money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are several international laws and agreements designed to combat money laundering. Some key examples include:\n\n1. The Financial Action Task Force (FATF) Recommendations\n- Global standard-setting body for anti-money laundering efforts\n- Provides guidelines for countries to implement\n\n2. United Nations Convention Against Transnational Organized Crime\n- Requires member states to criminalize money laundering\n- Promotes international cooperation in investigating and prosecuting money laundering\n\n3. Basel Committee on Banking Supervision guidelines\n- Sets international standards for banking regulations\n- Includes recommendations for preventing money laundering\n\n4. European Union Anti-Money Laundering Directives\n- Establishes uniform rules for financial institutions across EU countries\n- Requires customer due diligence and reporting of suspicious transactions\n\n5. Bank Secrecy Act (United States)\n- While primarily a U.S. law, it has international implications\n- Requires financial institutions to assist government agencies in detecting and preventing money laundering\n\nMost countries have their own national laws implementing these international standards, typically requiring financial institutions to:\n- Verify customer identities\n- Report suspicious transactions\n- Maintain transaction records\n- Implement internal compliance programs\n\nThese laws aim to prevent criminal organizations from disguising illegally obtained funds as legitimate income.",
